<sentence sentence-num-in-section="2" xml:id="C20.S3.F2.s1">
Figure 20.3.2: <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C20.S3.F2.m4">\theta_{1}\left(\pi x,q\right)</Math> , <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C20.S3.F2.m5">0\leq x\leq 2</Math> , <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C20.S3.F2.m6">q</Math> = 0.05, 0.5, 0.7, 0.9. For <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C20.S3.F2.m7">q\leq q^{\text{Dedekind}}</Math> , <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C20.S3.F2.m8">\theta_{1}\left(\pi x,q\right)</Math> is convex in <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C20.S3.F2.m9">x</Math> for <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C20.S3.F2.m10">0&amp;lt;x&amp;lt;1</Math> . Here <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C20.S3.F2.m11">q^{\text{Dedekind}}=e^{-\pi y_{0}}=0.1</Math>9 approximately, where <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C20.S3.F2.m12">y=y_{0}</Math> corresponds to the maximum value of Dedekind’s eta function <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C20.S3.F2.m13">\eta\left(iy\right)</Math> as depicted in Figure  .
</sentence>             
